<section><title> Solving 1st &amp; 2nd Order LHCC Equations </title>

	<introduction>
		<p>
			With the structure and solutions related to Linear Homogeneous Constant Coefficient (LHCC) equations established, we are now prepared to construct the general solution by combining the fundamental solutions that satisfy these equations.
		</p>

		<p>
			In this section, we will utilize the superposition principle to form the general solutions for LHCC equations. Additionally, we will explore how repeated and complex solutions to the characteristic equation affect the final form of the general solution for second-order and higher-order equations.
		</p>
	</introduction>

	<paragraphs><title> The General Solution to 1st and 2nd Order LHCC Equations </title>

				<example><title> Characteristic Equation &amp; Exponential Solutions </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					For each of the following equations, determine the characteristic equation and the fundamental exponential solutions.
				</p>
				<p>
					<sidebyside widths="40% 60%">
						<p>
							<line>	1.	<m>\ds\ 5y' + 6y = 0</m>	</line>
							<line>		<m></m>						</line>
						</p>
						<p>
							<solution>
								<p>
									Assuming <m>y = e^{rx}</m>, we have
								</p>
								<md>
									<mrow>	5\left[e^{rx}\right]' + 6\left[e^{rx}\right] = 0	\amp </mrow>
									<mrow>	5r e^{rx} + 6 e^{rx} = 0							\amp </mrow>
									<mrow>	(5r + 6) e^{rx} = 0									\amp </mrow>
								</md>.
								<p>
									Thus, the characteristic equation is
								</p>
								<me>
									5r + 6 = 0 \quad \Rightarrow \quad r = -\frac{6}{5}
								</me>,
								<p>
									and the fundamental solution is
								</p>
								<me>
									y = e^{-\frac{6}{5}x}.
								</me>
							</solution>
						</p>
					</sidebyside>
					<sidebyside widths="40% 60%">
						<p>
							<line>	2.	<m>\ds\ y'' - 4y = 0</m>	</line>
							<line>		<m></m>						</line>
						</p>
						<p>
							<solution>
								<p>
									Assuming <m>y = e^{rx}</m>, we have
								</p>
								<md>
									<mrow>	r^2 e^{rx} - 4 e^{rx} = 0	\amp </mrow>
									<mrow>	(r^2 - 4) e^{rx} = 0		\amp </mrow>
								</md>
								<p>
									Thus, the characteristic equation is
								</p>
								<md>
									<mrow>	r^2 -	\amp 4 = 0								</mrow>
									<mrow>			\amp \Rightarrow\ (r - 2)(r + 2) = 0	</mrow>
								</md>
								<p>
									and the fundamental solutions are
								</p>
								<me>
									y_1 = e^{2x}, \quad y_2 = e^{-2x}.
								</me>
							</solution>
						</p>
					</sidebyside>
					<sidebyside widths="40% 60%">
						<p>
							<line>	3.	<m>\ds\ y''' - 6y'' + y' - 6y = 0</m>	</line>
							<line>		<m></m>									</line>
						</p>
						<p>
							<solution>
								<p>
									Assuming <m>y = e^{rx}</m>, we have
								</p>
								<md>
									<mrow>	r^3 e^{rx} - 6r^2 e^{rx} + r e^{rx} - 6 e^{rx} = 0	\amp </mrow>
									<mrow>	(r^3 - 6r^2 + r - 6) e^{rx} = 0						\amp </mrow>
								</md>
								<p>
									Thus, the characteristic equation is
								</p>
								<me>
									r^3 - 6r^2 + r - 6 = 0
								</me>.
								<p>
									We can factor this as
								</p>
								<md>
									<mrow>	r^2(r - 6) + (r - 6) = 0	\amp </mrow>
									<mrow>	(r^2 + 1)(r - 6) = 0		\amp </mrow>
									<mrow>	r = -i,\ r = i,\ r = 6		\amp </mrow>
								</md>.
								<p>
									Therefore, the fundamental solutions are
								</p>
								<me>
									y_1 = e^{-ix}, \quad y_2 = e^{ix}, \quad y_3 = e^{6x}.
								</me>
							</solution>
						</p>
					</sidebyside>
				</p>
			</statement>
		</example>
		
		<p>

			This last example demostrates that, in general, an <m>n</m>-th order LHCC equation has <m>n</m> exponential solutions of the form <m>e^{rx}</m>, where <m>r</m> is a solution (real or complex) to the <m>n</m>-th degree characteristic equation.
		</p>
		
		<introduction>

			<p>
				We are now ready to discuss how to form the general solution to a Linear Homogeneous Constant Coefficient (LHCC) equation. Before we do, let's list out everything we know about LHCC equations so far.
			</p>

			<sidebyside widths="14% 86%">
				<p>
					✏️ <term>FACT 1</term>
				</p>
				<p>
					An <m>n</m>-th order of LHCC equation has the form
					<me>
						a_n\ y^{(n)} + a_{n-1}\ y^{(n-1)} + \cdots + a_2\ y'' + a_1\ y' + a_0\ y = 0
					</me>,
					where <m>a_n,\ a_{n-1},\ \ldots,\ a_2,\ a_1,\ a_0</m> are constants.
				</p>
			</sidebyside>

			<sidebyside widths="14% 86%">
				<p>
					✏️ <term>FACT 2</term>
				</p>
				<p>
					The <em>characteristic equation</em> of the LHCC equation is given by
					<me>
						a_n\ r^n + a_{n-1}\ r^{n-1} + \cdots + a_2\ r^2 + a_1\ r + a_0 = 0
					</me>,
					and has <m>n</m> solutions: <m>\ r_1,\ r_2,\ \dots,\ r_n</m> (real or complex).
				</p>
			</sidebyside>

			<sidebyside widths="14% 86%">
				<p>
					✏️ <term>FACT 3</term>
				</p>
				<p>
					The <em>fundamental solutions</em> to the LHCC equation are given by
					<me>
						y_1 = e^{r_1 x},\quad y_2 = e^{r_2 x},\quad \dots,\quad y_n = e^{r_n x},
					</me>
					where <m>r_1,\ r_2,\ \dots,\ r_n</m> are the solutions to the <em>characteristic equation</em>.
				</p>
			</sidebyside>

			<p>
				Now, we will explore how to combine these fundamental solutions to construct the <em>general solution</em> to any LHCC equation. This will allow us to capture all possible solutions to the differential equation, ensuring that we do not miss any.
			</p>

		</introduction>

		<p>
			In addition to these facts, the last thing that we need to start building the general solution is an important concept known as the <em>superposition principle</em>. 
		</p>

		<definition xml:id="superposition-principle-second-order"><title> 2nd Order Superposition Principle </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					If <m>y_1, y_2, \dots, y_n</m> are solutions to a homogeneous linear differential equation, then any combination:
				</p>

				<me>
					y = c_1\ y_1 + c_2\ y_2 + \dots + c_n\ y_n
				</me>

				<p>
					is also a solution for any constants <m>c_1, c_2, \dots, c_n</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</definition>

		<p>
			With this result and the above facts in hand, we can now construct the general solution to any LHCC equation as the sum of all its fundamental solutions. This gives us our fourth and final fact:
		</p>

		<sidebyside widths="14% 86%">
			<p>
				✏️ <term>FACT 4</term>
			</p>
			<p>
				For an <m>n</m>-th order LHCC equation, the general solution is
				<me>
					y = c_1\ y_1 + c_2\ y_2 + \cdots + c_n\ y_n,
				</me>
				where <m>c_1</m>, <m>c_2</m>, <m>\dots</m>, <m>c_n</m> are arbitrary constants and <m>y_1</m>, <m>y_2</m>, <m>\dots</m>, <m>y_n</m> are the fundamental solutions.
			</p>
		</sidebyside>

		<p>
			Now, let's put this into practice with some concrete examples.
		</p>

		<example><title> LHCC Equation General Solution </title>

			<p>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Find the general solution to each of the equation below.
					</p>
					<p>
						<sidebyside widths="40% 60%">
							<p>
								<line>	1.	<m>\ds\ y'+\pi\ y = 0</m>	</line>
								<line>		<m></m>						</line>
							</p>
							<p>
								<solution>
									<p>
										The characteristic equation
									</p>

									<me>
										r + \pi = 0
									</me>,

									<p>
										has the solution <m>r = -\pi</m>. So, the equation has a fundamental solution of the form
									</p>

									<me>
										y_1 = e^{-\pi x}
									</me>.

									<p>
										Since the equation is first-order, this is the only fundamental solution.
									</p>

									<p>
										Therefore, the general solution is
									</p>

									<me>
										y = c_1 e^{-\pi x}
									</me>.
								</solution>
							</p>
						</sidebyside>

						<sidebyside widths="40% 60%">
							<p>
								<line>	2.	<m>\ds\ \omega'' - 7\omega' = 0</m>	</line>
								<line>		<m></m>						</line>
							</p>
							<p>
								<solution>
									<p>
										The characteristic equation
									</p>

									<me>
										r^2 - 7r = 0
									</me>,

									<p>
										has the solutions <m>r = 0,\ 7</m>. So, the fundamental solutions are
									</p>

									<me>
										\omega_1 = e^{0x} = 1, \quad \omega_2 = e^{7x}
									</me>.

									<p>
										Since these are not like-terms, they are independent and by the superposition principle, the general solution is
									</p>

									<me>
										\omega = c_1 + c_2\ e^{7x}
									</me>.
								</solution>
							</p>
						</sidebyside>
						<sidebyside widths="40% 60%">
							<p>
								<line>	3.	<m>\ds\ 2\frac{d^{3}M}{dt^{3}} - 6\frac{dM}{dt} = 0</m>	</line>
								<line>		<m></m>									</line>
							</p>
							<p>
								<solution>
									<p>
										The characteristic equation
									</p>

									<me>
										2r^3 - 6r = 0
									</me>,

									<p>
										can be factored as
									</p>

									<md>
										<mrow>	2r(r^2 - 3) = 0	\amp </mrow>
									</md>.

									<p>
										So, <m>r = 0,\ \sqrt{3},\ -\sqrt{3}\ </m>, giving the 3 independent fundamental solutions
									</p>

									<me>
										e^{0t}, \quad e^{\sqrt{3}t}, \quad e^{-\sqrt{3}t}
									</me>.

									<p>
										By the superposition principle, the general solution is
									</p>

									<me>
										M(t) = c_1 + c_2 e^{\sqrt{3}t} + c_3 e^{-\sqrt{3}t}
									</me>.
								</solution>
							</p>
						</sidebyside>
					</p>
				</statement>
			</p>
		</example>

		<conclusion>
			<p>
				These examples illustrate how the general solution of an LHCC equation is created given the exponential functions that satisfy the equation. While the method is fairly straight forward, there are still a few details that need to be addressed. In particular, we will investigate what to do if the characteristic equations has <em>repeated solutions</em> and how to handle high order LHCC equations.
			</p>
		</conclusion>

		<exercise><title> Answer the Following </title>

			<task label="chkpt-general-solution-1"><title> Structure of the General Solution </title>
				<statement>
					<p>
						What is the general solution of a second-order LHCC equation if the characteristic equation has distinct real solutions <m>r_1</m> and <m>r_2</m>?
					</p>
				</statement>
				<choices>
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<p>
								<m>\quad y = c_1 e^{r_1 x} + c_1 e^{r_2 x}</m>
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. The constants must be distinct for each term.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice correct="yes">
						<statement>
							<p>
								<m>\quad y = c_1 e^{r_1 x} + c_2 e^{r_2 x}</m>
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Correct! Each fundamental solution is multiplied by an arbitrary constant.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<p>
								<m>\quad y = e^{r_1 x} + e^{r_2 x}</m>
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. The general solution includes arbitrary constants.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
				</choices>
			</task>

			<task label="chkpt-general-solution-2"><title> Understanding Arbitrary Constants </title>
				<statement>
					<p>
						How many arbitrary integration constants appear in the general solution of an <m>n</m>-th order LHCC equation?
					</p>
				</statement>
				<choices>
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<p>
								<m>\quad 0</m>
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. The answer is higher.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<p>
								<m>\quad 1</m>
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. The answer is higher.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<p>
								<m>\quad 2</m>
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. The answer is higher.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<p>
								<m>\quad n-1</m>
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. The answer is higher.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice correct="yes">
						<statement>
							<p>
								<m>\quad n</m>
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Correct! An <m>n</m>-th order LHCC equation must have <m>n</m> independent solutions, each multiplied by an arbitrary constant.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
				</choices>
			</task>

			<task label="chkpt-general-solution-3"><title> Matching Equations to Solutions </title>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Match each characteristic equation to its corresponding general solution.
					</p>
				</statement>
				<feedback>
					<p>
						Great work! The general solution is based on the characteristic solutions.
					</p>
				</feedback>
				<cardsort>
					<match>
						<premise><m>r^2 - 4 = 0</m></premise>
						<response><m>y = c_1 e^{2x} + c_2 e^{-2x}</m></response>
					</match>
					<match>
						<response><m>y = c_1 e^{4x} + c_2 e^{-4x}</m></response>
					</match>
					<match>
						<premise><m>r^2 - 3r - 4 = 0</m></premise>
						<response><m>y = c_1 e^{-x} + c_2 e^{4x}</m></response>
					</match>
					<match>
						<premise><m>r^2 - 2 = 0</m></premise>
						<response><m>y = c_1 e^{\sqrt{2}x} + c_2 e^{-\sqrt{2}x}</m></response>
					</match>
				</cardsort>
			</task>

			<task label="chkpt-general-solution-4"><title> Building Solutions </title>
				<statement correct="yes">
					<p>
						If <m>y_1</m> and <m>y_2</m> are solutions to a second-order LHCC equation, then
						<me>
							y = 5y_1 - 2y_2
						</me>
						is also a solution.
					</p>
				</statement>
				<feedback>
					<p>
						Correct! By the superposition principle, this combination is also a solution.
					</p>
				</feedback>
			</task>

			<task label="chkpt-general-solution-5"><title> Select the general solution </title>
				<statement>
					<p>
						What is the general solution for the first-order LHCC equation
						<me>y' - 2y = 0</me>?
					</p>
				</statement>
				<choices>
					<choice correct="no">
						<statement>
							<p>
								<m>\ds\quad y = ce^{2x}</m>
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. Check the sign of the exponent.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice correct="yes">
						<statement>
							<p>
								<m>\ds\quad y = ce^{-2x}</m>
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Correct! The solution has the form <m>y = ce^{rx}</m>, where <m>r</m> is found from the characteristic equation.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice correct="no">
						<statement>
							<p>
								<m>\ds\quad y = ce^{\frac12 x}</m>
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. Make sure to solve the characteristic equation correctly.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice correct="no">
						<statement>
							<p>
								<m>\ds\quad y = ce^{-\frac12 x}</m>
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. Check the coefficient of <m>y</m> in the original equation.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
				</choices>
			</task>

		</exercise>
	</paragraphs>

	<paragraphs><title> Second-Order Equations </title>
					
		<introduction>
			<p>
				The most important class of linear homogeneous constant coefficient (LHCC) equations are the second-order equations. This is because nearly every idea you learn for this order, extends to any higher-order case. For this discussion, we will explore the general solution to second-order LHCC equations and the different cases that arise based on the nature of the characteristic solutions. 
			</p>
		</introduction>

			<p>
				A <em>second-order LHCC equation</em> has the form:
			</p>

			<men xml:id="second-order-lhcc-de00">
				a y'' + b y' + c y = 0
			</men>

			<p>
				where <m>a, b, c</m> are constants. To solve such equations, we assume solutions of the form, <m>y = e^{rx}</m>, and determine the values of <m>r</m> that satisfy the equation. This leads to the <em>characteristic equation</em>:
			</p>

			<men xml:id="second-order-lhcc-characteristic-equation00">
				a r^2 + b r + c = 0
			</men>

			<p>
				Since this is a quadratic equation, we can solve it using the quadratic formula:
			</p>

			<me>
				r = \frac{-b \pm \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}
			</me>

			<p>
				If you need a refresher on quadratic equations, take a minute to review it <xref ref="solving-the-quadratic-equation" text="custom">HERE</xref>.
			</p>

			<p>
				Depending on the value of the <em>discriminant</em>, <m>\Delta = b^2 - 4ac</m>, we classify solutions into three distinct cases:
			</p>
	</paragraphs>

	<paragraphs><title> <m>\Delta &gt; 0</m>: Real, Non-Repeating Solutions </title>
		<p>
			If <m>\Delta</m> is positive, then characteristic equation has two distinct real solutions,
		</p>

		<me>
			r_1 = \frac{-b + \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}, \quad
			r_2 = \frac{-b - \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}
		</me>,

		<p>
			and the general solution is simply
		</p>

		<me>
			y = c_1 e^{r_1 x} + c_2 e^{r_2 x}
		</me>.

		<example><title> Standard Case Examples </title>

			<p>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Find the general solutions to each 2nd-order LHCC equation.
					</p>

					<sidebyside widths="45% 55%">
						<p>
							<p>
								<m>\ds y'' - 5y' + 6y = 0</m>
							</p>
							<p>
								<solution>
									<p>
										The characteristic equation
									</p>

									<me>
										r^2 - 5r + 6 = 0
									</me>

									<p>
										can be factored as
									</p>

									<me>
										(r - 2)(r - 3) = 0
									</me>,

									<p>
										which gives the non-repeating real solutions
									</p>

									<me>
										r_1 = 2, \qquad r_2 = 3
									</me>
									
									<p>
										and the general solution
									</p>

									<me>
										y = c_1 e^{2x} + c_2 e^{3x}
									</me>
								</solution>
							</p>
						</p>
						<p>
							<p>
								<m>\ds 5y'' + 13y' - 2y = 0</m>
							</p>
							<p>
								<solution>
									<p>
										The characteristic equation is 
									</p>

									<me>
										5r^2 + 9r - 2 = 0
									</me>.

									<p>
										Using the quadratic formula,
									</p>

									<md>
										<mrow> r	\amp = \frac{-9 \pm \sqrt{9^2 - 4 (5)(-2)}}{2 \cdot 5}	</mrow>
										<mrow>		\amp = \frac{-9 \pm \sqrt{121}}{10}						</mrow>
										<mrow>		\amp = \frac{-9 \pm 11}{10}								</mrow>
									</md>,

									<p>
										we get the real and non-repeating solutions
									</p>

									<me>
										r_1 = -2, \quad r_2 = \frac{1}{5}
									</me>,

									<p>
										which lead to the general solution
									</p>

									<me>
										y = c_1 e^{-2x} + c_2 e^{\frac{1}{5}x}
									</me>.
								</solution>
							</p>
						</p>
						
					</sidebyside>
				</statement>
			</p>
			
		</example>
	</paragraphs>

	<paragraphs><title> <m>\Delta = 0</m>: Real, Repeating Solutions </title>
		<p>
			If <m>\Delta</m> is zero, then the characteristic equation has the <em>repeated solutions</em>
		</p>

		<me>
			r_1 = \frac{-b + 0}{2a} = \frac{-b}{2a}, \quad r_2 = \frac{-b - 0}{2a} = \frac{-b}{2a}
		</me>.

		<p>
			Setting this up in the usual manner gives the general solution:
		</p>

		<me>
			y = c_1 e^{r_1 x} + c_2 e^{r_1 x} \qquad (r_1 = r_2)
		</me>.

		<p>
			This results in <em>like-terms</em> that combine into <m>(c_1 + c_2) e^{r_1 x}</m>, making it incomplete for a second-order LHCC equation, which needs two independent solutions. To address this, we modify the second fundamental solution as:
		</p>

		<me>
			y = c_1 e^{r_1 x} + c_2 x e^{r_1 x}
		</me>

		<p>
			This modification ensures that our solution has two independent terms and preserves the desired properties of exponential functions that make them compatible solutions.
		</p>

		<example><title> Repeated Case Examples </title>
			<p>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Find the general solutions to each 2nd-order LHCC equation.
					</p>

					<sidebyside widths="45% 55%">
						<p>
							<p>
								<m>\ds y'' + 4y' + 4y = 0</m>
							</p>
							<p>
								<solution>
									<p>
										The characteristic equation
									</p>

									<me>
										r^2 + 4r + 4 = 0
									</me>

									<p>
										can be factored as
									</p>

									<me>
										(r + 2)(r + 2) = 0
									</me>

									<p>
										which gives the repeating real solutions
									</p>

									<me>
										r_1 = -2, \qquad  r_2 = -2
									</me>

									<p>
										and modified general solution
									</p>

									<me>
										y = c_1 e^{-2x} + c_2 x e^{-2x}
									</me>.
								</solution>
							</p>
						</p>

						<p>
							<p>
								<m>\ds 16\frac{d^2q}{dr^2} - 8\frac{dq}{dr} + q = 0</m>
							</p>
							<p>
								<solution>
									<p>
										The characteristic equation is:
									</p>

									<me>
										16r^2 - 8r + 1 = 0
									</me>

									<p>
										Using the quadratic formula,
									</p>

									<md>
										<mrow> r	\amp = \frac{8 \pm \sqrt{8^2 - 4 (16)(1)}}{2 \cdot 16}	</mrow>
										<mrow>		\amp = \frac{8 \pm \sqrt{0}}{32}					</mrow>
										<mrow>		\amp = \frac{8}{32}	= \frac{1}{4}						</mrow>
									</md>,

									<p>
										This shows that <m> r = \frac{1}{4} </m> is a repeated root and the general solution is
									</p>

									<me>
										q(r) = c_1 e^{\frac{1}{4}r} + c_2 r e^{\frac{1}{4}r}
									</me>
									
								</solution>
							</p>
						</p>
					</sidebyside>
				</statement>
			</p>
		</example>
	</paragraphs>

	<paragraphs><title> <m>\Delta &lt; 0</m>: Two Complex Solutions </title>
		<p>
			If <m>\Delta</m> is negative, the characteristic equation has two <em>complex conjugate solutions</em>:
		</p>

		<me>
			r_1 = \alpha + i \beta, \quad r_2 = \alpha - i \beta
		</me>

		<p>
			and the independent fundamental solutions are:
		</p>

		<me>
			y_1 = e^{(\alpha + i \beta)x}, \quad y_2 = e^{(\alpha - i \beta)x}
		</me>.

		<p>
			In the complex case, it is standard to express these as <em>sine</em> and <em>cosine</em> (via <xref ref="eulers-formula" text="title"/>) so that the general solution can be written as 
		</p>

		<me>
			y = e^{\alpha x} (c_1 \cos(\beta x) + c_2 \sin(\beta x))
		</me>.

		<example><title> Complex Case Examples </title>
			<p>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Find the general solutions to each 2nd-order LHCC equation.
					</p>

					<sidebyside widths="50% 50%">

						<p>
							<p>
								<m>\ds \omega'' + 4\omega' + 5\omega = 0</m>
							</p>
							<p>
								<solution>
									<p>
										The characteristic equation
									</p>

									<me>
										r^2 + 4r + 5 = 0
									</me>.

									<p>
										is solved with the quadratic formula:
									</p>

									<md>
										<mrow> r	\amp = \frac{-4 \pm \sqrt{4^2 - 4 (1)(5)}}{2 \cdot 1}	</mrow>
										<mrow> 		\amp = \frac{-4 \pm 2i}{2} = -2 \pm i					</mrow>
									</md>.

									<p>
										Using <m>\alpha = -2</m> and <m>\beta = 1</m> in the complex formula, we get the general solution
									</p>

									<me>
										\omega(t) = c_1 e^{-2t}\left(c_1\cos t + c_2\sin t\right)
									</me>
								</solution>
							</p>
						</p>

						<p>
							<p>
								<m>\ds y'' + 25y = 0</m>
							</p>
							<p>
								<solution>
									<p>
										The characteristic equation
									</p>

									<me>
										r^2 + 25 = 0
									</me>

									<p>
										has the complex solutions
									</p>

									<me>
										r = \pm 5i
									</me>.

									<p>
										Using <m>\alpha = 0</m> and <m>\beta = 5</m> in the complex case formula, we get the general solution
									</p>

									<me>
										y = e^{0x}\left(c_1\cos(5x) + c_2\sin(5x)\right)
									</me>

									<p>
										or simply
									</p>

									<me>
										y = c_1\cos(5x) + c_2\sin(5x)
									</me>
								</solution>
							</p>
						</p>
						
					</sidebyside>
				</statement>
			</p>
		</example>
	</paragraphs>

	<p>
		Every second-order LHCC differential equation will fall into one of these three cases. For reference, here is a summary of each case.
	</p>

	<assemblage><title> ✳️ 2nd-Order LHCC General Solution Cases </title>
		<p>
			Let <m>r_1</m>, <m>r_2</m> be the characteristic solutions of a 2nd-order LHCC equation.
			<dl width="wide">
				<li xml:id="lhcc-case-1"><title> Standard Case </title>
					<p>
						If <m>r_1 \ne r_2</m>, then the general solution is
						<me>
							y = c_1 e^{r_1 x} + c_2 e^{r_2 x}
						</me>
					</p>
				</li>
				<li xml:id="lhcc-case-2"><title> Repeated Case </title>
					<p>
						If <m>r_1 = r_2</m>, then the general solution is
						<me>
							y = c_1 e^{r_1 x} + c_2 x e^{r_1 x}
						</me>
					</p>
				</li>
				<li xml:id="lhcc-case-3"><title> Complex Case </title>
					<p>
						If <m>r_1, r_2=\alpha \pm i\beta</m>, then the general solution is
						<me>
							y = e^{\alpha x} (c_1 \cos(\beta x) + c_2 \sin(\beta x))
						</me>
					</p>
				</li>
			</dl>
		</p>
	</assemblage>

	<conclusion>
		<p>
			These examples illustrate how second-order LHCC equations are solved using the <em>standard</em>, <em>repeating</em>, and <em>complex</em> cases discussed above. In the next section, we will see that a similar process can be generalized to higher-order LHCC equations.
		</p>
	</conclusion>

	<exercise><title>Answer the Following</title>

		<task label="chkpt-second-order-lhcc-1"><title> Discriminant of the Characteristic Equation </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					If the discriminant of the characteristic equation is <m>-4</m>, then what kind of solutions does the characteristic equation have?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
			<choice correct="no">
				<statement>
					<p>
						Real and equal solutions
					</p>
				</statement>
				<feedback>Incorrect. The discriminant is the number under the square root in the quadratic formula.</feedback>
			</choice>
			<choice correct="no">
				<statement>
					<p>
						Real and unequal solutions
					</p>
				</statement>
				<feedback>Incorrect. The discriminant is the number under the square root in the quadratic formula.</feedback>
			</choice>
			<choice correct="yes">
				<statement>
					<p>
						Complex solutions
					</p>
				</statement>
				<feedback>Correct! A negative discriminant indicates the square root of a negative number in the quadratic formula, which results in the complex number <m>i</m>.</feedback>
			</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-second-order-lhcc-2"><title> Classifying Characteristic Equations </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Match each characteristic equation to the correct root type.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<feedback>
				<p>
					Good work! The discriminant helps classify root types.
				</p>
			</feedback>
			<cardsort>
				<match>
					<premise><m>r^2 - 4r + 3 = 0</m></premise>
					<response>Two distinct real roots</response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>r^2 - 6r + 9 = 0</m></premise>
					<response>One repeated real root</response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>r^2 + 4 = 0</m></premise>
					<response>Complex roots</response>
				</match>
			</cardsort>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-second-order-lhcc-3"><title> Discriminant and Solution Type </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					For a second-order LHCC equation with characteristic equation,
				</p>

				<me>
					r^2 + br + c = 0
				</me>,

				<p>
					which expression determines the form of the general solution?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad\ds b - 4c</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The discriminant is given by a squared term.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad\ds b^2 - 4c</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct! The discriminant determines whether the characteristic roots are real and distinct, real and repeated, or complex.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad\ds b^2 + 4c</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The correct expression involves a subtraction.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad\ds \sqrt{b^2 - 4c}</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The discriminant does not include a square root.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-second-order-lhcc-4"><title> Solving the characteristic equation </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					If the characteristic equation for an LHCC equation is <m>r^2 - 4r + 4 = 0</m>, what is the general solution?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad y = c_1 e^{2x} + c_2 x e^{2x}</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>Correct! The solution <m>r = 2</m> has a multiplicity of 2.</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="no">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad y = c_1 e^{2x} + c_2 e^{2x}</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>Incorrect. The solution <m>r = 2</m> has a multiplicity of 2.</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="no">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad y = c_1 e^{2x} + c_2 e^{-2x}</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>Incorrect. Ensure you solve the charactistic equation correctly.</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="no">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad y = e^{2x}(c_1 \cos(2x) + c_2 \sin(2x))</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>Incorrect. The characteristic equation does not have complex solutions.</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-second-order-lhcc-5"><title> Purely Imaginary Characteristic Solutions </title>
			<statement correct="yes">
				<p>
					If a characteristic equation has roots <m>\pm i</m>, the general solution is
					<me>
						y = c_1 \cos x + c_2 \sin x
					</me>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<feedback>
				<p>
					Correct! The complex exponentials transform into sine and cosine terms.
				</p>
			</feedback>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-second-order-lhcc-6"><title> Match the Characteristic &amp; General Solutions </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Match the characteristic solutions to the corresponding general solution.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<cardsort>
				<match>
					<premise><m>\small r = 5 </m></premise>
					<response><m>\small C e^{5x} </m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>\small r_1 = 2, \ r_2 = 3 </m></premise>
					<response><m>\small C_1 e^{2x} + C_2 e^{3x} </m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>\small r_1 = -1, \ r_2 = -4 </m></premise>
					<response><m>\small C_1 e^{-x} + C_2 e^{-4x} </m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>\small r_1 = 3 + 2i, \ r_2 = 3 - 2i </m></premise>
					<response><m>\small e^{3x} (C_1 \cos(2x) + C_2 \sin(2x)) </m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>\small r_1 = -2, \ r_2 = -2 </m></premise>
					<response><m>\small (C_1 + C_2 x) e^{-2x} </m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>\small r_1 = -1 + i, \ r_2 = -1 - i </m></premise>
					<response><m>\small e^{-x} (C_1 \cos(x) + C_2 \sin(x)) </m></response>
				</match>
			</cardsort>
		</task>

	</exercise>

</section>